Hello Vishnu,
 
Thanks for contacting GitLab Support, and for the detailed write-up.
 
Based on the behavior you described, this is most likely a combination of downstream protected branch permissions and downstream job rules.
 
In a multi-project trigger, GitLab still evaluates whether the triggering user is allowed to create a pipeline on the target branch of the downstream project, so if that branch is protected, users who are not allowed on that branch can see the downstream pipeline created but with no runnable jobs.
 
 
Addressing your expected behaviour:
 
What you are seeing is expected behavior for multi-project downstream pipelines.
 
When you use trigger: project, GitLab evaluates the downstream pipeline using the identity of the user who triggered the upstream pipeline/job. This is especially important when the downstream pipeline targets a protected branch. In that case, the triggering user must be allowed to run pipelines against that protected branch in the downstream project as well.
 
Because of that, your current expectation:
application repo Maintainers can trigger deployments,
without direct access to the deployment repo,
while deployment branches remain protected
is not something trigger: project can provide by itself.
 
So for the model you want, the recommended approach is to decouple deployment authorization from the triggering user. In practice, that means using the Trigger pipelines API with a dedicated service account, bot user,  pipeline trigger token, or project or group access token that does have permission to start the deployment pipeline, rather than relying on the end user’s identity through trigger: project.
 
That pattern allows you to:
keep the deployment repository restricted,
keep deployment branches protected,
and still let application teams initiate deployments without giving them direct membership in the deployment project.
 
The trade-off is that this is not the native trigger: project CI configuration. 
 
Here is an example, using a CI/CD job with a pipeline trigger token:
 
.trigger_cd:
  stage: deploy
  variables:
    DEPLOYMENT_BRANCH: "feature/deploy-cicd"
    SERVICE_NAME: "${CI_PROJECT_NAME}"
    VERSION: "${VERSION}"
  script:
    - >
      curl --fail --request POST
      --form token="$DEPLOY_TRIGGER_TOKEN"
      --form ref="$DEPLOYMENT_BRANCH"
      --form "variables[SERVICE_NAME]=$SERVICE_NAME"
      --form "variables[VERSION]=$VERSION"
      "${CI_API_V4_URL}/projects/<deployment_project_id>/trigger/pipeline"
 
 
If you want to keep passing more values that you were previously forwading with forward: then you need to send each one explicitly, for example:
 
.trigger_cd:
  stage: deploy
  variables:
    DEPLOYMENT_BRANCH: "feature/deploy-cicd"
    SERVICE_NAME: "${CI_PROJECT_NAME}"
    VERSION: "${VERSION}"
  script:
    - >
      curl --fail --request POST
      --form token="$DEPLOY_TRIGGER_TOKEN"
      --form ref="$DEPLOYMENT_BRANCH"
      --form "variables[SERVICE_NAME]=$SERVICE_NAME"
      --form "variables[VERSION]=$VERSION"
      --form "variables[ENV]=$ENV"
      --form "variables[CHART_NAME]=$CHART_NAME"
      "${CI_API_V4_URL}/projects/<deployment_project_id>/trigger/pipeline"
 
 
 
Notes:
DEPLOY_TRIGGER_TOKEN should be a pipeline trigger token created in the deployment project.
<deployment_project_id> should be replaced with the numeric project ID of itepaypg-sbiepay2/infra/devops/deployment.
Because this uses the API instead of trigger: project, strategy: depend and forward: no longer apply.
You also don't see the downstream multi-project pipeline relationship in the pipeline graph.
 
There is an existing feature request proposal to address this: https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/-/work_items/352127 I recommend you weigh in there and subscribe if it interests you to have native support for this authorization model.
 
 
Best,
Mike
